{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "BlackbodyRadiation",
        "description": "Planck's blackbody radiation law (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 4, Eq. 4.2) — the monochromatic emissive power F_B_λ of a blackbody at temperature T as a function of wavelength λ via Planck's constant h, the speed of light c, and the Boltzmann constant k_B: F_B_λ = 2π·c²·h·λ⁻⁵ / (exp(c·h/(k_B·λ·T)) - 1). The component is observed-only: one algebraic equation on one state variable (F_B_λ the monochromatic emissive power per unit wavelength in W/m³) driven by two input parameters (T temperature in K, λ wavelength in m) and four constants (h Planck's constant, c speed of light, k_B Boltzmann constant, π_val mathematical π as a Float64 value). No time derivatives, no PDE, no coupling. Migrated from GasChem.jl@8c12c048 src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:73 (`BlackbodyRadiation` @component). The Planck function is the spectral energy density of thermal radiation from an opaque, non-reflective body in thermodynamic equilibrium — the foundational equation of quantum radiative transfer. Integrating F_B_λ over all wavelengths gives the Stefan-Boltzmann total flux σT⁴ (see stefan_boltzmann.esm); the wavelength where F_B_λ peaks is λ_max = b/T from Wien's displacement law (see wien.esm). At the default T=5800 K (Sun's effective surface temperature) and λ=500 nm (visible green, the canonical solar-peak wavelength), F_B_λ ≈ 8.46e13 W/m³ — the peak intensity that anchors the Sun's irradiance at Earth's distance and the solar-driven photochemistry of the atmosphere. At T=300 K (Earth surface) and λ=10 μm (thermal-IR), F_B_λ ≈ 3.12e7 W/m³ — the canonical longwave outgoing radiation peak that drives the planetary energy balance.",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "radiation",
            "blackbody",
            "planck",
            "observed-only",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-4gsh)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H. and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Hoboken, NJ. Chapter 4 (The Earth's Climate System), §4.1 (Radiation), Eq. 4.2, p. 99 — Planck's blackbody radiation law F_B_λ = 2πc²h/λ⁵ · 1/(exp(ch/kλT) - 1) relating monochromatic emissive power to wavelength and temperature."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Planck, M. (1901). Ueber das Gesetz der Energieverteilung im Normalspectrum. Annalen der Physik, 309(3), 553-563. The original derivation of the spectral distribution from quantum-statistical reasoning that resolved the ultraviolet catastrophe of classical Rayleigh-Jeans theory and inaugurated quantum physics."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "BlackbodyRadiation": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:73\n\nUpstream `BlackbodyRadiation` is an MTK `@component` declaring four `@constants` (`h` = 6.626e-34 J·s Planck's constant; `c` = 2.9979e8 m/s speed of light; `k_B` = 1.381e-23 J/K Boltzmann's constant; `π_val` = Float64(π) = 3.141592653589793 dimensionless — explicitly stored as a Float64 to avoid Julia's automatic Irrational→BigFloat promotion inside MTK's symbolic expressions), two `@parameters` (`T` = 5800.0 K, the temperature input — the upstream default is the Sun's effective surface temperature; `λ` = 5.0e-7 m, the wavelength input — the upstream default is 500 nm matching the canonical visible-green solar-peak wavelength), one time-indexed `@variables` (`F_B_λ` — algebraic monochromatic emissive power in W/m³ with no derivative), and one algebraic equation (`F_B_λ ~ 2 * π_val * c^2 * h * λ^(-5) / (exp(c * h / (k_B * λ * T)) - 1)`). Identical structure preserved here. Upstream structural test (`Structural: BlackbodyRadiation system`, test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:52-59) asserts `length(equations(bb)) == 1` and `length(unknowns(bb)) == 1` and that the system compiles — matched here by the single entry in `equations` and the single state-typed variable (F_B_λ) plus the six input-typed parameters (h, c, k_B, π_val, T, λ).\n\nThe four upstream `@constants` (h, c, k_B, π_val) are encoded here as `type: parameter` with the upstream default values, matching the rig-wide convention used by sibling radiation migrations (photon_energy.esm at components/gaschem/radiation/photon_energy.esm encodes its h and c `@constants` the same way; wien.esm at components/gaschem/radiation/wien.esm encodes its b `@constants` the same way; stefan_boltzmann.esm at components/gaschem/radiation/stefan_boltzmann.esm encodes its σ `@constants` the same way; chapman.esm at components/gaschem/stratospheric/chapman.esm encodes its four `@constants` k2_A/k4_A/C_k4/T_ref the same way). This makes h, c, k_B, and π_val overridable from a downstream consumer's `parameter_overrides` block — useful for unit-test variants (e.g., the CODATA-2019 exact values h = 6.62607015e-34 J·s and c = 2.99792458e8 m/s and k_B = 1.380649e-23 J/K vs the upstream rounded 6.626e-34, 2.9979e8, 1.381e-23) and for sensitivity studies that probe the Planck-function prefactor. The two upstream `@parameters` (T, λ) are `type: parameter` with their upstream defaults of 5800.0 K and 5.0e-7 m — already MTK parameters upstream, so the parameter-vs-constant distinction collapses at the `.esm` schema level.\n\nObservability classification: this component is observed-only — the output variable F_B_λ is given by a single algebraic equation in the inputs (no time derivative, the `(t)` time index has no role since there is no `D(·)` operator in the equation). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0.0, 1.0]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files in this rig (photon_energy.esm, wien.esm, stefan_boltzmann.esm at components/gaschem/radiation/, typical.esm at components/gaschem/combined/typical.esm) — algebraic identities have no time dependence and converge to the same fixed-point value regardless of the sampling time.\n\nPhysics structure: Planck's law (S&P Eq. 4.2) is the canonical spectral energy density of a blackbody in thermodynamic equilibrium — the resolution of the classical ultraviolet catastrophe in the Rayleigh-Jeans theory of cavity radiation. The formula has two factors: the prefactor 2πc²h/λ⁵ rising sharply at short wavelengths (the wavelength-fifth divergence), and the Bose-Einstein occupation factor 1/(exp(ch/kλT) - 1) damping the short-wavelength rise via the exponential. The product peaks at λ_max = b/T (Wien's law, see wien.esm) and integrates over all λ to give the Stefan-Boltzmann total flux σT⁴ (see stefan_boltzmann.esm). The two limiting forms:\n  • Rayleigh-Jeans (low frequency, ch ≪ kλT): exp(x) - 1 ≈ x giving F_B_λ ≈ 2πckT/λ⁴ (classical equipartition limit)\n  • Wien tail (high frequency, ch ≫ kλT): exp(x) ≫ 1 giving F_B_λ ≈ 2πc²h/λ⁵ · exp(-ch/(kλT)) (exponential cutoff)\nThe 2π factor (rather than π) gives the hemispherical emissive power per unit wavelength integrated over the outward-facing 2π solid angle — the quantity directly usable in radiative-transfer codes that distinguish upwelling vs downwelling flux.\n\nNumerical defaults (S&P Page 99, solar-peak canonical):\n  h    = 6.626e-34         J·s   (Planck's constant, 4-digit-rounded CODATA value)\n  c    = 2.9979e8          m/s   (speed of light, 5-digit-rounded value)\n  k_B  = 1.381e-23         J/K   (Boltzmann constant, 4-digit-rounded CODATA value)\n  π_val= 3.141592653589793 1     (Float64(π), explicit double-precision π)\n  T    = 5800.0            K     (Sun's effective surface temperature)\n  λ    = 5.0e-7            m     (visible-green wavelength, ~500 nm)\nAt these defaults the Planck function gives F_B_λ = 84565887378394.64 W/m³ ≈ 8.46e13 W/m³. This matches the upstream test `Equation: BlackbodyRadiation (Eq. 4.2)` at test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:151-165 which asserts F_B_λ ≈ 8.46e13 W/m³ at rtol=5e-2 with the default (T=5800, λ=5e-7) parameters. The migration tightens the assertion to rel=1e-9 on the exact IEEE-754 result. The factor evaluates via the chain c·h/(k_B·λ·T) = 1.986307254e-25 / 4.0049e-26 ≈ 4.9599 (dimensionless), exp(4.9599) - 1 ≈ 141.59, prefactor 2π·c²·h·λ⁻⁵ ≈ 1.1975e16, ratio ≈ 8.4566e13 W/m³ — the canonical solar-peak spectral irradiance.\n\nUpstream test reproduction:\n- The upstream `Structural: BlackbodyRadiation system` test (test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:52-59) asserts the system has 1 equation and 1 unknown and compiles — reproduced by the test-level shape (1 entry in `equations`, 1 state-typed variable F_B_λ).\n- The upstream `Equation: BlackbodyRadiation (Eq. 4.2)` test (test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:151-165) asserts at default T=5800/λ=5e-7 that F_B_λ ≈ 8.46e13 W/m³ at rtol=5e-2, and at T=300/λ=1e-5 (Earth thermal-IR peak) that F_B_λ ≈ 3.13e7 W/m³ at rtol=5e-2. Reproduced and tightened by `upstream_solar_peak_5800K_500nm` (pins F_B_λ = 84565887378394.64 W/m³ at rel=1e-9) and `upstream_earth_thermal_300K_10um` (pins F_B_λ = 31217606.963872723 W/m³ at rel=1e-9).\n- The upstream `Limiting: Blackbody radiation non-negative for all positive T and λ` test (test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:305-328) sweeps T ∈ {100, 300, 1000, 5800, 10000} K × λ ∈ {1e-7, 1e-6, 1e-5, 1e-4} m and asserts F_B_λ ≥ 0 across all 20 combinations, then asserts F_B_λ > 0 strictly at three physically-relevant (T, λ) points. Reproduced by 20 `nonneg_T*_lam*` tests pinning the actual IEEE-754 value at each combination — the strict-positivity bound is implicit in pinning a positive value, and the underflow case (T=100, λ=1e-7) is pinned to 0.0 with abs=1e-12 (the integer denominator `exp(arg) - 1` for arg ≈ 1438 returns Inf in IEEE-754; numerator/Inf = +0.0). The three strictly-positive anchor cases `strict_positive_solar_visible_5800K_500nm` / `strict_positive_earth_thermal_300K_10um` / `strict_positive_intermediate_1000K_3um` pin the actual IEEE-754 values for the (T, λ) triples called out in the upstream test.\n- The upstream `Analytical: Planck spectrum peak matches Wien prediction` test (test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:423-453) asserts at T ∈ {300, 1000, 5800} K that F_B_λ(T, λ_peak) > F_B_λ(T, 0.9·λ_peak) AND F_B_λ(T, λ_peak) > F_B_λ(T, 1.1·λ_peak), where λ_peak = 2.897e-3 / T is the Wien-displacement peak. The .esm runner does not directly support cross-test inequality assertions, so reproduced by pinning the actual IEEE-754 values at the three Wien-peak wavelengths and the two off-peak wavelengths (0.9·λ_peak and 1.1·λ_peak) for each temperature — by the IEEE-754 monotonicity of the Planck-function near its maximum, the strict inequality F_peak > F_0.9 and F_peak > F_1.1 is exact at machine precision. Nine tests total: `wien_peak_match_T<T>K` for T ∈ {300, 1000, 5800} with three sub-tests each (`_at_peak`, `_below_peak_0.9`, `_above_peak_1.1`).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): observed-only algebraic system with the Planck function — five floating-point ops on the prefactor (constant×constant×^××× with 5 ops, ~5 ULP accumulated), three ops in the exponent (one division, one multiplication chain ×k_B×λ×T, ~3 ULP), one transcendental exp() (~1-2 ULP for high-quality libm), one subtraction (exp - 1), one final division — total ~10-15 ULP of accumulated error. For Float64 magnitudes ranging from 0.0 (underflow case) to ~1e14 (default), the ULP-relative error is ~5e-16 to ~5e-15, comfortably below the rel=1e-9 tolerance bound with ~6 orders of magnitude headroom. Matches the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files in this rig with similar exp-containing closed-form expressions (surface_energy_flux.esm at rel=1e-9 for its `exp(...)` term; offline_mode_forcing.esm at rel=1e-8 on the longwave tests for its single `exp(idso_T_ref/T)`); the rel=1e-9 here is the slightly tighter bound supported by the Planck function's simpler exp() chain. `abs=1e-12` floors the underflow case (T=100, λ=1e-7 → exp(1438) overflows to Inf in IEEE-754, F_B_λ = finite/Inf = +0.0) without false-negative on the relative bound. The upstream Julia tests use rtol=5e-2 (the equation-verification tests at default and Earth-thermal conditions) — re-asserted here at the much tighter uniform rel=1e-9 model-level.\n\nUnit balance (verified): the single equation balances dimensionally. `F_B_λ ~ 2 * π_val * c^2 * h * λ^(-5) / (exp(c * h / (k_B * λ * T)) - 1)`. Numerator: (1) · (m/s)² · (J·s) · (m)⁻⁵ = m²/s² · J·s · m⁻⁵ = J·s⁻¹·m⁻³ = W·m⁻³. Denominator: dimensionless (the argument c·h/(k_B·λ·T) has units (m/s · J·s)/(J/K · m · K) = (J·m)/(J·m) = 1, so exp(·) is dimensionless and exp(·) - 1 is dimensionless). Ratio: W·m⁻³ ✓. The migrated `.esm` preserves the upstream units verbatim — h in J·s, c in m/s, k_B in J/K, π_val dimensionless, T in K, λ in m, F_B_λ in W/m³. SI throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime.\n\nGreek-character preservation: the upstream uses Greek λ for wavelength and π_val for the explicit Float64 π constant; both are preserved verbatim here (matching the sibling photon_energy.esm convention which also keeps λ as Greek). The output F_B_λ is also kept as the upstream identifier with a Greek λ subscript — distinguishing it from the integrated quantity F_B (W/m²) in stefan_boltzmann.esm and the absorbed/emitted fluxes F_S and F_L (also W/m²) in planetary_energy_balance.esm. The Greek-vs-ASCII choice is consistent with the photon_energy.esm sibling that also keeps Δε, ν, and λ in Greek; the stratospheric chapman.esm sibling that keeps k2, k4, T, M, O, O3, Ox as ASCII; and the surface_energy_flux.esm sibling that translates Greek to ASCII (σ_SB → sigma_SB, ε_g → epsilon_g) — the rig convention is per-file, with this file following the radiation_fundamentals.jl sibling pattern of preserving the upstream Greek identifiers."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-9,
                "abs": 1.0e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "h": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J*s",
                    "default": 6.626e-34,
                    "description": "Planck's constant (S&P Page 99, 4-digit-rounded CODATA value). The fundamental quantum of action that anchors the discrete photon picture and the Bose-Einstein occupation factor in Planck's law. The upstream default 6.626e-34 J·s is the historical 4-digit-rounded value; the modern CODATA-2019 exact definition is h = 6.62607015e-34 J·s (the SI redefinition of the kilogram fixes h to this value exactly). The two differ by ~1e-5 relative — well within the rtol=5e-2 upstream test gate, encoded as a parameter so downstream consumers can override h to the modern CODATA value for precision applications without forking the component."
                },
                "c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 2.9979e8,
                    "description": "Speed of light in vacuum (S&P Page 99, 5-digit-rounded value). The upstream default 2.9979e8 m/s is the historical 5-digit-rounded value; the modern CODATA-1983 exact definition is c = 2.99792458e8 m/s (the SI redefinition of the meter fixes c to this value exactly via the meter being defined as the distance light travels in 1/299792458 s). The two differ by ~8e-7 relative — well within the rtol=5e-2 upstream test gate, encoded as a parameter to support CODATA-precision overrides."
                },
                "k_B": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/K",
                    "default": 1.381e-23,
                    "description": "Boltzmann constant (S&P Page 99, 4-digit-rounded CODATA value). The fundamental quantity linking thermal-statistical mechanics (mean energy per degree of freedom = (1/2)k_B·T) and macroscopic thermodynamics; appears in the Bose-Einstein occupation factor exp(hν/kT) - 1 of Planck's law. The upstream default 1.381e-23 J/K is the historical 4-digit-rounded value; the modern CODATA-2019 exact definition is k_B = 1.380649e-23 J/K (the SI redefinition of the kelvin fixes k_B to this value exactly via the Boltzmann constant becoming a defining constant). The two differ by ~3e-4 relative — within the rtol=5e-2 upstream test gate, encoded as a parameter to support precision overrides."
                },
                "π_val": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 3.141592653589793,
                    "description": "Mathematical pi as a Float64 constant (Float64(π) in Julia, ~3.141592653589793). Encoded explicitly as a fixed-default parameter because the upstream Julia source declares `π_val = Float64(π)` as a `@constants` — the conversion to Float64 is required to avoid Julia's automatic Irrational→BigFloat promotion inside MTK's symbolic expressions. The upstream default value is the IEEE-754 double-precision representation of π (3.141592653589793 = the round-to-nearest-even of the exact mathematical π); this exact bit pattern is preserved here. Downstream consumers needing extended precision (e.g., quad-precision sensitivity studies) can override π_val, but the default matches Julia's `Float64(π)` exactly."
                },
                "T": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 5800.0,
                    "description": "Temperature of the emitting blackbody (S&P Page 99). The upstream default 5800.0 K is the Sun's effective surface temperature — sometimes given as 5778 K (the modern IAU 2015 value derived from the Sun's total luminosity and radius) but the upstream uses the classic 5800 K round figure. At this temperature paired with the default λ=500 nm wavelength, Planck's law gives F_B_λ ≈ 8.46e13 W/m³ — the canonical solar-peak spectral irradiance per unit wavelength that anchors the Sun's irradiance at Earth's distance and the solar-driven photochemistry of the atmosphere. Other canonical temperatures: 300 K (Earth surface) gives a thermal-IR peak at ~9.66 μm with F_B_λ at 10 μm ≈ 3.12e7 W/m³, 3 K (CMB) gives a microwave peak at ~0.97 mm, 1e4 K (cool-star photosphere or stellar corona) gives a UV/X-ray peak shifted by Wien's law."
                },
                "λ": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 5.0e-7,
                    "description": "Wavelength of the emitted photon (S&P Page 99, visible-green canonical default). The upstream default 5.0e-7 m = 500 nm is the yellow-green visible peak that matches Wien's law applied to T_sun ≈ 5800 K and anchors the solar-peak photon used in actinic-flux and spectral-irradiance calculations. Other canonical wavelengths used in atmospheric radiative-transfer applications: 200-300 nm (UV-B/UV-C, the Hartley-Huggins ozone-photolysis bands O3 + hν → O + O2), 300-400 nm (UV-A, the O3 + hν → O(1D) + O2 channel and NO2-photolysis band), 400-700 nm (visible, solar-energy-balance photometric range), 700-3000 nm (near-IR, solar-IR component), 3-50 μm (thermal-IR, the Earth-radiation longwave range), 1 mm (microwave, the cosmic-microwave-background Wien peak)."
                },
                "F_B_λ": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "W/m^3",
                    "description": "Monochromatic blackbody emissive power in watts per cubic meter (W·m⁻³ = W·m⁻²·m⁻¹, i.e., emitted power per unit area per unit wavelength). Equivalently called the spectral radiance per unit wavelength integrated over the outward 2π hemisphere. F_B_λ(λ, T) gives the wavelength-resolved emission of a thermal source: integrating over all wavelengths recovers the total emissive power F_B = ∫₀^∞ F_B_λ dλ = σT⁴ (Stefan-Boltzmann; see stefan_boltzmann.esm), and the wavelength where F_B_λ is maximized is λ_max = b/T (Wien's law; see wien.esm). At the default solar-peak (T=5800, λ=500 nm), F_B_λ ≈ 8.46e13 W/m³ — the canonical solar-peak spectral irradiance per unit wavelength used in radiative-transfer codes to bin solar energy across the visible band. At the Earth-thermal peak (T=300, λ=10 μm), F_B_λ ≈ 3.12e7 W/m³ — the canonical longwave outgoing radiation peak driving the planetary energy balance (S&P Eq. 4.6 / planetary_energy_balance.esm)."
                }
            },
